english:
  title: Preface to Poems on the Departure of Governor Jeong, Administrator of Sangju
  author: Lee Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Ceremonial Official An Ja-ok came to me and said, "My uncle, Governor Jeong of Sangju, is departing for his post. The learned gentlemen have already composed poems for the occasion. You have long been close to my uncle—surely you cannot remain silent? I beg you to write a preface to their verses."

    Once I visited the Governor's residence, and he spoke to me thus: "Sunheung is my mother's native place, where the Lady resides. She is advanced in years, with no other brothers to sustain her with filial care, and I too have been distant, rarely hearing her news. How can my heart forget her even for a day? My presence here is bound only by office, which I shall one day resign. Should Heaven grant me a nearby prefecture where I might nurture her in her final years—that would be fortune itself."

    Now this appointment has come to pass. Sangju lies but a few days' journey from Sunheung, the very place where my uncle-by-marriage, Master Gyeonjae, once served. Long ago, when Gyeonjae held the post of Censor, he came to govern this same district, also seeking to provide for his aging parents. Is the Governor's departure mere coincidence? Heaven surely supports his filial devotion. My own ancestor too once held this office and never ceased praising Gyeonjae's administration, even warning me: "Gyeonjae was a filial son at home, a loyal minister at court, and an upright official in the provinces. You must emulate him."

    When I myself governed this district—not ten years after Gyeonjae's time—I took him as my model. Later, when I traveled through Sangju and met with the elders, I found his benevolent influence still flourishing, undiminished. Now the Governor serves in the Censor's office with forthright speech and righteous countenance, bringing order to the court. Yet scholars feared his talents would not advance further. That he has suddenly received this provincial post is truly for the sake of the Lady. In his governance, let him follow Gyeonjae's example: as Gyeonjae served the Lady with devotion, so should he; as Gyeonjae governed his people with wisdom, so should he. This is what he must do, and what we all expect of him.

    Moreover, the new king has assumed the throne, and his great ministers work in harmony to reform the realm. Both the central ministries and the provincial offices seek capable men. The imperial directive states that governors shall be evaluated by five measures. Let the Governor attend to these: when taxation weighs heavily, lighten it; when litigation multiplies, simplify it; when households diminish, increase them; when fields lie fallow, bring them under cultivation; when bandits arise, suppress them. If he labors day and night to fulfill these duties, he will be a true upright official and a true filial son. In serving his duties as a minister lies the perfection of his duties as a son. Thus I write this preface.
  footnotes:
    - Gyeonjae (謹齋) was a renowned official known for integrity in both his family life and public service, serving as a model of virtue across all stations of life.
    - The "five measures" refer to standard criteria for evaluating provincial administrators' performance in taxation, justice, population, agriculture, and security.
    - The Governor's appointment to Sangju, near his mother's birthplace, is presented as Heaven's reward for his filial piety rather than mere administrative efficiency.
